          of a person, left out a Bill of Rights, and has been amended 27 times in 235 years. It's
          still the most influential governance document ever written — not because it was perfect,
          but because it was concrete enough to argue about, ratify, and then fix.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          <strong>This document is wrong too.</strong> Parts of it, anyway. I know that because nothing
          this ambitious is right on the first try.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          But for 20 years I've heard "elections are broken" from every direction — and not a single
          concrete, technical proposal that anyone can actually build from, critique, or improve.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4 font-bold">So here's one. A full blueprint for voter verification that:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-8 mb-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Doesn't require showing ID every time you vote</li>
          <li>
            Catches cryptographic conflicts in real time; other fraud signals are handled through
            fast asynchronous review
          </li>
          <li>Designed so no single operator category can unilaterally finalize records</li>
          <li>Doesn't track how you vote</li>
          <li>No direct fee to voters; funded through public budgets</li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://electionlab.mit.edu/research/cost-of-conducting-elections"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              class="text-navy-600 underline hover:text-gold-600 transition-colors"
              >One widely cited estimate</a
            > puts U.S. election administration spending at $4-6 billion per cycle. This aims to detect
            core conflicts in seconds and resolve disputed cases through audited adjudication.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mb-4">
          This isn't blockchain crypto bro nonsense. There are no tokens. No fees. No speculation.
          It's a permissioned government system — like a shared, tamper-proof ledger that federal,
          state, and independent auditors all have to agree on before anything is recorded.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          <strong>This isn't a voting machine. It doesn't touch your ballot.</strong> It only answers
          four questions:
        </p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-3 my-6">
          <div class="votechain-question-card border-2 border-gold-500 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
